{"title_page": "James Wiggin Coe", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=James Coe\n|birth_name=James Wiggins Coe\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1909|6|13}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1943|9|28|1909|6|13}}\n|birth_place= [[Richmond, Indiana]], U.S.\n|death_place= Presumed [[South China Sea]]\n|placeofburial= \n|placeofburial_label=\n|image=James Wiggin Coe.jpg\n|image_size= 200px\n|caption= Commander James Wiggins Coe\n|nickname=Red\n|allegiance= {{Flag|United States of America|1896}}\n|branch= {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears= 1926\u20131943\n|rank= [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|24px]] [[Commander (United States)]]\n|servicenumber= 0-063137\n|commands= {{USS|S-39}}<br>{{USS|Skipjack|SS-184}}<br>{{USS|Cisco|SS-290}}\n|unit=\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n|awards= [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]<br/>[[Purple Heart]]\n|laterwork= \n|signature= \n}}\n\nCommander '''James Wiggins \"Red\" Coe''' (June 13, 1909 \u2013 September 28, 1943 (missing), January 8, 1946 (presumed dead) was an [[United States|American]] submariner. A [[submarine ace]],<ref>Blair (1975) p. 110-133.</ref> Coe commanded {{USS|Skipjack|SS-184|6}} and {{USS|Cisco|SS-290|2}} during operations in the [[Pacific Ocean theater of World War II|Pacific theatre]] of [[World War II]].<ref name=\"bio\" /> After a number of successful patrols, Coe and the ''Cisco'' failed to return from patrol in November 1943, and her captain and crew were presumed dead in 1946.\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[Richmond, Indiana]], Coe attended [[Richmond High School (Richmond, Indiana)|Morton High School]] and then the [[US Naval Academy]] and [[Annapolis]], [[Maryland]]. Commissioned in June 1930, he served aboard {{USS|Nevada|BB-36|6}} and then {{USS|Chicago|CA-29|6}}. From 1931 he commenced training in submarines, and served on {{USS|S-27}} in 1933, followed by {{USS|S-29}} in 1935 and {{USS|S-33}} in 1937. \n\nAfter two years back in the United States as an instructor, he took command of {{USS|S-39}} in January 1940 and, after the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor, he commanded her during three war patrols in the Southeast Asia.  On March 4, 1942, Coe commanded ''S-39'' when she attacked and sank a Japanese tanker in [[Sunda Strait]].\n\nCoe transferred to the USS ''Skipjack'' in March 1942.<ref name=\"bio\" /> <ref>http://uboat.net/allies/commanders/3149.html</ref>\n\n==''Skipjack''==\nCoe commanded ''Skipjack'' for three war patrols (''Skipjack'''s third, forth and fifth) during which he sank four Japanese merchant ships and damaged another.  \n\nWhile in command of the ''Skipjack'', he wrote a letter to his superiors in the supply division complaining about a lack of toilet paper aboard his vessel. Included in the memorandum was \"a sample of the desired material\" to help supply identify the item being requested, while commenting that in the mean time \"personnel during this period has become accustomed to the use of \u201cErsatz\u201d the vast amount of incoming non-essential paper work\" and closing with the remark that \"in order to cooperate in war effort at small local sacrifice, the SKIPJACK desires no further action to be taken until the end of current war which has created a situation aptly described as \u201cWar is Hell\u201d.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/library/research-guides/z-files/zc-ship-files-in-the-navy-department-library-s/uss-skipjack-toilet-paper-memorandum.html |title=U.S.S. SKIPJACK - Toilet Paper Memorandum |publisher=Navy Department Library |accessdate=June 7, 2015 |author=Naval History Division |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816030310/http://www.history.navy.mil/research/library/research-guides/z-files/zc-ship-files-in-the-navy-department-library-s/uss-skipjack-toilet-paper-memorandum.html |archivedate=August 16, 2015 }}</ref> The letter later served as inspiration for a scene in the 1959 comedy film ''[[Operation Petticoat]]''.   Coe's letter and the roll of toilet paper are preserved at the [[Submarine Force Library and Museum]] in [[Groton, Connecticut]].\n\nCoe also fired the first [[Mark 14 torpedo]] to be shot with its magnetic influence disabled as part of a new test run ordered by Rear-Admiral [[Charles A. Lockwood]], which took place off of [[King George Sound]] in June 1942.<ref>Blair (1975) p. 276.</ref>\n\n==USS ''Cisco'' and death==\nCoe was appointed prospective commanding officer of the USS ''Cisco'' in January 1943.  He became the submarine's first commanding officer when it was commissioned on May 10.  He was awarded the [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]] \"for extraordinary heroism\" while serving in the Pacific sinking Japanese merchant shipping. \n\nIn September 1943, ''Cisco'' sailed on its first war patrol to the [[South China Sea]], where his submarine was presumed lost in action.  (Postwar analysis concluded that ''Cisco'' was sunk by Japanese forces on September 28.)  Coe was posthumously awarded the [[Purple Heart]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/bios/coe_jamesw.htm |title=Biography - Commander James Wiggins Coe, USN |publisher=Navy Department Library |date=August 17, 1949 |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |author=Naval History Division |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122082716/http://www.history.navy.mil/bios/coe_jamesw.htm |archivedate=January 22, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Japanese ships sunk by submarines under Coe's command==\n*March 4, 1942 - USS ''S-39'' sank fleet tanker ''Erimo'' (6500 GRT).\n*May 6, 1942 - USS ''Skipjack'' sank transport ship ''Kanan Maru'' (2567 GRT).\n*May 8, 1942 - USS ''Skipjack'' sank transport ship ''Bujun Maru'' (4804 GRT).\n*May 17, 1942 - USS ''Skipjack'' sank troop transport ''Tazan Maru'' (5477 GRT).\n*October 14, 1942 - USS ''Skipjack'' sank transport ship ''Shunko Maru'' (6780 GRT).\n\nSource - [http://uboat.net/allies/commanders/3149.html U-Boat.net]\n\n==Legacy==\nCoe's successful patrols with the ''Skipjack'' and his command of the ''Cisco'' gave him some notoriety, leading to his name appearing in a contemporary list of the  ''Top Skippers of World War II By Number of Confirmed Kills''. \n\nA military rest camp in [[Subic Bay]] in the [[Philippines]] \u2013 part of the [[U.S. Naval Base Subic Bay]] \u2013 is named in his honour, as is a street in [[Naval Station Pearl Harbor]].<ref>Gugliotta (2000) p. 213-214.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Navy Cross]]\n*[[Purple Heart]] (posthumous)\n*[[American Defense Service Medal]] with \"FLEET\" clasp\n*[[Asiatic-Pacific Campaign Medal]] with five [[battle star]]s\n*[[World War II Victory Medal]] (posthumous)\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n;Sources\n* {{cite book | last = Blair | first = Clay, Jr. | authorlink = Clay Blair | year = 1975 | title = Silent victory: the U.S. submarine war against Japan | location = Philadelphia | publisher = Lippincott | pages =  | isbn = 978-0-397-00753-0 | oclc = 821363 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/silentvictoryus00blai }}\n* {{cite book | title=Pigboat 39: An American Sub Goes to War | publisher=University Press of Kentucky | author=Gugliotta, Bobette | year=2000 | isbn=0813128307}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coe, James Wiggin}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Richmond, Indiana]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:20th-century American naval officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States submarine commanders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=James Coe\n|birth_name=James Wiggins Coe\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|df=yes|1909|6|13}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|df=yes|1943|9|28|1909|6|13}}\n|birth_place= [[Richmond, Indiana]], U.S.\n|death_place= Presumed [[South China Sea]]\n|placeofburial= \n|placeofburial_label=\n|image=James Wiggin Coe.jpg\n|image_size= 200px\n|caption= Commander James Wiggins Coe\n|nickname=Red\n|allegiance= {{Flag|United States of America|1896}}\n|branch= {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears= 1926\u20131943\n|rank= [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|24px]] [[Commander (United States)]]\n|servicenumber= 0-063137\n|commands= {{USS|S-39}}<br>{{USS|Skipjack|SS-184}}<br>{{USS|Cisco|SS-290}}\n|unit=\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n|awards= [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]]<br/>[[Purple Heart]]\n|laterwork= \n|signature= \n}}\n\nCommander '''James Wiggins \"Red\" Coe''' (13 June 1909 \u2013 28 September 1943 (missing), 8 January 1946 (presumed dead) was an [[United States|American]] submariner. A [[submarine ace]],<ref>Blair (1975) p. 110-133.</ref> Coe commanded {{USS|Skipjack|SS-184|6}} and {{USS|Cisco|SS-290|2}} during operations in the [[Pacific Ocean theater of World War II|Pacific theatre]] of [[World War II]].<ref name=\"bio\" /> After a number of successful patrols, Coe and the ''Cisco'' failed to return from patrol in November 1943, and her captain and crew were presumed dead in 1946.\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[Richmond, Indiana]], Coe attended [[Richmond High School (Richmond, Indiana)|Morton High School]] and then the [[US Naval Academy]] and [[Annapolis]], [[Maryland]]. Commissioned in June, 1930, he served aboard {{USS|Nevada|BB-36|6}} and then {{USS|Chicago|CA-29|6}}. From 1931 he commenced training in submarines, and served on {{USS|S-27}} in 1933, followed by {{USS|S-29}} in 1935 and {{USS|S-33}} in 1937. \n\nAfter two years back in the United States as an instructor, he took command of {{USS|S-39}} in January 1940 and, after the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor, he commanded her during three war patrols in the Southeast Asia.  On March 4, 1942, Coe commanded ''S-39'' when she attacked and sank a Japanese tanker in [[Sunda Strait]].\n\nCoe transferred to the USS ''Skipjack'' in March 1942.<ref name=\"bio\" /> <ref>http://uboat.net/allies/commanders/3149.html</ref>\n\n==''Skipjack''==\nCoe commanded ''Skipjack'' for three war patrols (''Skipjack'''s third, forth and fifth) during which he sank four Japanese merchant ships and damaged another.  \n\nWhile in command of the ''Skipjack'', he wrote a letter to his superiors in the supply division complaining about a lack of toilet paper aboard his vessel. Included in the memorandum was \"a sample of the desired material\" to help supply identify the item being requested, while commenting that in the mean time \"personnel during this period has become accustomed to the use of \u201cErsatz\u201d the vast amount of incoming non-essential paper work\" and closing with the remark that \"in order to cooperate in war effort at small local sacrifice, the SKIPJACK desires no further action to be taken until the end of current war which has created a situation aptly described as \u201cWar is Hell\u201d.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/library/research-guides/z-files/zc-ship-files-in-the-navy-department-library-s/uss-skipjack-toilet-paper-memorandum.html |title=U.S.S. SKIPJACK - Toilet Paper Memorandum |publisher=Navy Department Library |accessdate=7 June 2015 |author=Naval History Division |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816030310/http://www.history.navy.mil/research/library/research-guides/z-files/zc-ship-files-in-the-navy-department-library-s/uss-skipjack-toilet-paper-memorandum.html |archivedate=16 August 2015 }}</ref> The letter later served as inspiration for a scene in the 1959 comedy film ''[[Operation Petticoat]]''.   Coe's letter and the roll of toilet paper are preserved at the [[Submarine Force Library and Museum]] in [[Groton, Connecticut]].\n\nCoe also fired the first [[Mark 14 torpedo]] to be shot with its magnetic influence disabled as part of a new test run ordered by Rear-Admiral [[Charles A. Lockwood]], which took place off of [[King George Sound]] in June 1942.<ref>Blair (1975) p. 276.</ref>\n\n==USS ''Cisco'' and death==\nCoe was appointed prospective commanding officer of the USS ''Cisco'' in January 1943.  He became the submarine's first commanding officer when it was commissioned on May 10.  He was awarded the [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]] \"for extraordinary heroism\" while serving in the Pacific sinking Japanese merchant shipping. \n\nIn September 1943, ''Cisco'' sailed on its first war patrol to the [[South China Sea]], where his submarine was presumed lost in action.  (Postwar analysis concluded that ''Cisco'' was sunk by Japanese forces on September 28.)  Coe was posthumously awarded the [[Purple Heart]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/bios/coe_jamesw.htm |title=Biography - Commander James Wiggins Coe, USN |publisher=Navy Department Library |date=17 August 1949 |accessdate=27 January 2014 |author=Naval History Division |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122082716/http://www.history.navy.mil/bios/coe_jamesw.htm |archivedate=22 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Japanese ships sunk by submarines under Coe's command==\n*4 March 1942 - USS ''S-39'' sank fleet tanker ''Erimo'' (6500 GRT).\n*6 May 1942 - USS ''Skipjack'' sank transport ship ''Kanan Maru'' (2567 GRT).\n*8 May 1942 - USS ''Skipjack'' sank transport ship ''Bujun Maru'' (4804 GRT).\n*17 May 1942 - USS ''Skipjack'' sank troop transport ''Tazan Maru'' (5477 GRT).\n*14 October 1942 - USS ''Skipjack'' sank transport ship ''Shunko Maru'' (6780 GRT).\n\nSource - [http://uboat.net/allies/commanders/3149.html U-Boat.net]\n\n==Legacy==\nCoe's successful patrols with the ''Skipjack'' and his command of the ''Cisco'' gave him some notoriety, leading to his name appearing in a contemporary list of the  ''Top Skippers of World War II By Number of Confirmed Kills''. \n\nA military rest camp in [[Subic Bay]] in the [[Philippines]] \u2013 part of the [[U.S. Naval Base Subic Bay]] \u2013 is named in his honour, as is a street in [[Naval Station Pearl Harbor]].<ref>Gugliotta (2000) p. 213-214.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Navy Cross]]\n*[[Purple Heart]] (posthumous)\n*[[American Defense Service Medal]] with \"FLEET\" clasp\n*[[Asiatic-Pacific Campaign Medal]] with five [[battle star]]s\n*[[World War II Victory Medal]] (posthumous)\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n;Sources\n* {{cite book | last = Blair | first = Clay, Jr. | authorlink = Clay Blair | year = 1975 | title = Silent victory: the U.S. submarine war against Japan | location = Philadelphia | publisher = Lippincott | pages =  | isbn = 978-0-397-00753-0 | oclc = 821363 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/silentvictoryus00blai }}\n* {{cite book | title=Pigboat 39: An American Sub Goes to War | publisher=University Press of Kentucky | author=Gugliotta, Bobette | year=2000 | isbn=0813128307}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coe, James Wiggin}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Richmond, Indiana]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:20th-century American naval officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States submarine commanders]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Wiggin_Coe"}
{"title_page": "Kirori Mal College", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2017}}\n{{Advert|date=April 2017}}\n{{Cleanup university|date=April 2017}}}}\n{{Infobox college\n| name                 = Kirori Mal College\n| image                = \n| established          = 1954\n| type                 = Government Supported\n| nickname             = KMC\n| academic_affiliation = [[University of Delhi]]\n| principal            = Dr. Vibha Singh Chauhan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmcollege.com/administration.jsp|title=Kirori Mal College, University Of Delhi Powered By : Redox Technologies Pvt. Ltd.|website=Kmcollege.com|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n| address              = [[University of Delhi|North Campus]], University Enclave\n| coordinates          = {{Coord|28|40|57|N|77|12|23|E|display=inline,title}}\n| website              = {{url|http://www.kmcollege.ac.in/}}\n| city                 = New Delhi\n| parent               = \n| state                = Delhi\n| country              = India\n| logo                 = }}\n[[File:Kmcfront.jpg|thumb|Arts and Humanities Department Building]]\n'''Kirori Mal College''' is one of the constituent college of the [[University of Delhi]], located in the '''North Campus''' of DU, in [[New Delhi]], [[India]]. Established in 1954.<ref>[http://web.du.ac.in/collegedetails.htm?college_name=Kirori%20Mal%20College] {{dead link|date=November 2017}}</ref> [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]] accredited it with a CGPA of 3.54(A++)<ref>[[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=November 2019}} in 2016, which is third highest among all [[Delhi University]] colleges.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20161114045646/http://duexpress.in/2016/11/08/srcc-bags-top-spot-in-naac-grading-2016-followed-by-lsr-kmc]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmcollege.ac.in/colleges/newsevents/1127080320170906381.03.2017%20(1).pdf|title=Certificate of accreditation|website=Kmcollege.ac.in|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n|type=College\n|NIRF_C_2019=18}}\n\n==Introduction==\nKirori Mal College is a co-educational constituent college and a part of north campus, University of Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.du.ac.in/du/index.php?page=kirori-mal-college|title=Kirori Mal College - University of Delhi|website=Du.ac.in|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe college shifted to its present campus on 1 February 1954. The college celebrated its Golden Jubilee in February 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiaranker.com/colleges/delhi-university|title=Top Delhi University (DU) Colleges 2014|website=indiaranker.com|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==College societies==\nKirori Mal College has activities in drama, debate, music, fine arts, photography, Astronomy, Robotics, Environment, dance and film. Notable among them is \"Sensation\u201d the dance society consisting two wings one choreography and one western, putting up 2 productions each year the society has achieved many accomplishments which helped them to attain the ECA quota in the year 2019. The Physics department of the college has its own Astronomy and Robotics Club.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/theatre-enthusiasts-flock-to-kirori-mal/article3612868.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=Theatre enthusiasts flock to Kirori Mal | date=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-06-22/delhi/27827189_1_societies-kirori-mal-amitabh-bachchan|title=All the world's a stage at DU|date=Jun 22, 2006|work=The Times of India|first1=Abantika|last1=Ghosh}}</ref> \"MUSOC\"  is one of the top music societies of India .\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{alumni|date=March 2018}}\n{{more citations needed section|date=April 2019}}\nKirori Mal College has a large alumni base. Notable members include:-\n\n===Actors, directors and singers===\n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA ARTICLE-->\n\n* [[Amitabh Bachchan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/headlines-today-top-stories/story/amitabh-bachchans-journey-to-the-top-58283-2009-10-10|title=Amitabh Bachchan's journey to the top|last=October 10|first=Headlines Today|last2=October 10|first2=2009UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-04-22|last3=Ist|first3=2009 14:45}}</ref> - Actor\n* [[KK (singer)|KK]]{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} - Playback Singer\n* [[Ravi Baswani]] - film actor\n* [[Shakti Kapoor]]{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} - actor\n* [[Satish Kaushik]]{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} - Indian film director, producer and actor\n* [[Kulbhushan Kharbanda]]{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} - actor\n* [[Siddharth Narayan]] - actor\n* [[Prashant Narayanan]] - actor\n* [[Sanam Puri]] - Singer\n* [[Vijay Raaz]] - film actor\n* [[Divyendu Sharma]] - actor\n* [[Sushant Singh]] - film and television actor\n* [[Mohammed Zeeshan Ayyub]] -  actor\n* [[Ali Abbas Zafar]] - director\n* [[Vijay Krishna Acharya]] -  screenwriter and director\n* [[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]] - director\n* [[Anant Vidhaat Sharma]] - actor\n* [[Sargun Mehta]] - television actress\n* [[Sonam Sherpa]] musician [[ Parikrama]]\n*  Utpal Kumar Singh -IAS -Chief Secretary of Uttarakhand.\n* Satish Kumar -Food Corporation of India\n\n===Politicians===\n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA ARTICLE-->\n* [[Naveen Patnaik]] -Indian politician, Chief Minister of [[Odisha]], India and the chief of Biju Janata Dal, a regional political party in Odisha. He is a writer and has published three books\n* [[Madan Lal Khurana|Madanlal Khurana]] - former Chief Minister of Delhi\n* [[Rangarajan Kumaramangalam]] -politician\n* [[Girija Prasad Koirala|G.P. Koirala]] -  Former Prime Minister of Nepal\n* [[Pravesh Verma]], Delhi politician\n\n===Others===\n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA ARTICLE-->\n\n* [[Padmavathy Bandopadhyay]] - first woman Air Marshal of Indian Air Force\n* [[Habib Faisal]] - Hindi screenwriter and director\n* [[Gaurav Bidhuri]] - boxer who won medal at World Championship\n* [[Mohan Singh Kohli|M.S. Kohli]] - Indian mountaineer\n* [[Massoud Khalili]]\n* [[M. S. Krishnan]] -Chair of Business Information Technology at the University of Michigan's Ross School of Business\n* [[Abhay Kumar]] - poet, artist and diplomat\n* [[Sanjivan Lal]] - film maker\n* [[Harbans Mukhia]] - Indian historian \n* [[Saeed Naqvi]] - journalist\n* [[Parikrama (band)|Parikrama]] - band\n* [[Justice Raghuvendra Singh Rathore|Raghuvendra Singh Rathore]]\n* [[Rajshekhar]] -Indian lyricist\n* [[Himanshu Sharma]] - Bollywood screenwriter\n* [[Mrityunjay Kumar Singh]] \n* [[Dinesh Thakur]] - theatre director\n* [[Mirza Waheed]] - Writer\n*[[Nikhil Madan]] - Professor\n* [[Arjun Dev]]- Writer, Educationist and Historian, he co-wrote some of the extremely popular NCERT books<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/arjun-dev-a-legendary-historian-passes-away/article31201575.ece</ref><ref>https://thewire.in/education/arjun-dev-historian-tribute</ref>\n\n===Notable faculty===\n* [[Hiren Gohain]]\n* [[Krishna Kumar (educationist)|Krishna Kumar]]\n* [[Sarup Singh]] (ex-VC, University of delhi and former governor of kerela and Gujarat )\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.kmcollege.ac.in/}}\n\n{{University of Delhi}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Delhi]]\n[[Category:University of Delhi]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1954]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Commerce colleges in India]]\n[[Category:Science colleges in India]]\n[[Category:Arts colleges in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2017}}\n{{Advert|date=April 2017}}\n{{Cleanup university|date=April 2017}}}}\n{{Infobox college\n| name                 = Kirori Mal College\n| image                = \n| established          = 1954\n| type                 = Government Supported\n| nickname             = KMC\n| academic_affiliation = [[University of Delhi]]\n| principal            = Dr. Vibha Singh Chauhan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmcollege.com/administration.jsp|title=Kirori Mal College, University Of Delhi Powered By : Redox Technologies Pvt. Ltd.|website=Kmcollege.com|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n| address              = [[University of Delhi|North Campus]], University Enclave\n| coordinates          = {{Coord|28|40|57|N|77|12|23|E|display=inline,title}}\n| website              = {{url|http://www.kmcollege.ac.in/}}\n| city                 = New Delhi\n| parent               = \n| state                = Delhi\n| country              = India\n| logo                 = }}\n[[File:Kmcfront.jpg|thumb|Arts and Humanities Department Building]]\n'''Kirori Mal College''' is one of the constituent college of the [[University of Delhi]], located in the '''North Campus''' of DU, in [[New Delhi]], [[India]]. Established in 1954.<ref>[http://web.du.ac.in/collegedetails.htm?college_name=Kirori%20Mal%20College] {{dead link|date=November 2017}}</ref> [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]] accredited it with a CGPA of 3.54(A++)<ref>[[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=November 2019}} in 2016, which is third highest among all [[Delhi University]] colleges.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20161114045646/http://duexpress.in/2016/11/08/srcc-bags-top-spot-in-naac-grading-2016-followed-by-lsr-kmc]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmcollege.ac.in/colleges/newsevents/1127080320170906381.03.2017%20(1).pdf|title=Certificate of accreditation|website=Kmcollege.ac.in|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n|type=College\n|NIRF_C_2019=18}}\n\n==Introduction==\nKirori Mal College is a co-educational constituent college and a part of north campus, University of Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.du.ac.in/du/index.php?page=kirori-mal-college|title=Kirori Mal College - University of Delhi|website=Du.ac.in|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe college shifted to its present campus on 1 February 1954. The college celebrated its Golden Jubilee in February 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiaranker.com/colleges/delhi-university|title=Top Delhi University (DU) Colleges 2014|website=indiaranker.com|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==College societies==\nKirori Mal College has activities in drama, debate, music, fine arts, photography, Astronomy, Robotics, Environment, dance and film. Notable among them is \"Sensation\u201d the dance society consisting two wings one choreography and one western, putting up 2 productions each year the society has achieved many accomplishments which helped them to attain the ECA quota in the year 2019. The Physics department of the college has its own Astronomy and Robotics Club.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/theatre-enthusiasts-flock-to-kirori-mal/article3612868.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=Theatre enthusiasts flock to Kirori Mal | date=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-06-22/delhi/27827189_1_societies-kirori-mal-amitabh-bachchan|title=All the world's a stage at DU|date=Jun 22, 2006|work=The Times of India|first1=Abantika|last1=Ghosh}}</ref> \"MUSOC\"  is one of the top music societies of India .\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{alumni|date=March 2018}}\n{{more citations needed section|date=April 2019}}\nKirori Mal College has a large alumni base. Notable members include:-\n\n===Actors, directors and singers===\n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE 